text: Beutiful Park! With great views! Beutiful trees, flowers and shrubbery. Great walking and cycling tracks, monuments and memorials, there's also a large kids playground and exercise area. Beutiful spot to see the sunset, have a walk or picnic. Look out for the beutiful birdlife while walking through the area
author: Sim W

text: Nice place to walk along the water, looking out onto Beagle Gulf Bay. Lots of people walk there, and there are seats where you can just sit and read and relax. Close to the CBD as well.
author: Lorraine Hétu Manifold

text: It's a good place to work out. I love this place. It has great equipments for calisthenics.
author: Shaikat Barua

text: I enjoyed a morning walk at Bicentennial Park in Darwin and found it to be a nice experience. The park is beautifully maintained, with lush greenery and well-paved paths that make for an easy and pleasant stroll. The views of the harbor and surrounding nature are breathtaking, especially in the morning light. The park's tranquil atmosphere, combined with the gentle breeze from the water, provides a refreshing start to the day. There are plenty of benches and shaded areas to relax and take in the scenery. It's also a great spot for jogging or a leisurely walk.
author: TOMIO YAMAZAKI

text: We had the absolute best time exploring Litchfield National Park with our guide Aaron. From start to finish, he was knowledgeable, friendly, and made the whole experience unforgettable. He shared so many interesting facts about the history, wildlife, and landscapes, and had a great sense of humor that kept the day fun. Aaron made sure everyone felt comfortable and included, and he went above and beyond to make the tour special. Swimming in the waterfalls, spotting wildlife, and learning about the park wouldn’t have been the same without his guidance. Highly recommend Aaron to anyone visiting Litchfield, he truly made the day one to remember!
author: Alex O'Reilly

text: This was the best tour I’ve ever been on! Our guide Aaron was incredibly knowledgeable and shared so much fascinating information about the local plants and wildlife. He even let us try the unique taste of some special ants, which was such a fun experience! We visited three beautiful pools for refreshing swim, and the lunch he provided was absolutely delicious. On the way, he also stopped by a farm and let us pet an adorable little piglet – such a lovely surprise! I would highly recommend this tour to anyone. It was truly unforgettable!! Thank you Aaron
author: Joyce X

text: I had the best experience I could’ve asked for! Aaron was absolutely amazing, he went above and beyond to show us everything and teach us along the way. I wouldn’t hesitate to join the tour again and 100% recommend it to everyone. We did the Litchfield Park + Berry Springs tour with Aaron, and it was unforgettable!
author: Sophia Felix

text: Fantastic day in a small group (11) tour with a knowledgable and informative guide, Aaron. A relaxed pace even though we packed a lot in - three swim spots (avoiding the crowds), interesting roadside stops to learn about flora and fauna, leisurely and tasty picnic lunch, drink stop on the return at the very unusual but lovely Butterfly House! Highly recommend.
author: Meg

text: I loved my tour with Litchfield Park adventures. Not only was the scenery spectacular, our tour guide, Aaron really knows his stuff. Plus he’s so personable and made us all feel so welcome it was like a day out with an old friend. Highly recommend.
author: Beth Martin

text: Great waterside venue with a magnificent sunset over the ocean. Bring a pillow for comfort. Strictly smoke free - excellent. Food and drinks available, plus a variety of seating options - arrive quite early to get good seats.
author: Harry Hoogendoorn

text: Superb showcase featuring Michael Atkinson 'Modern Day Castaway'. You can buy drinks and food and I believe the food options changes weekly based on who is catering. Roughly $8-12 for a meal, bottle of wine was $30.
author: famousaj1

text: Beautiful scenery. Lovely atmosphere. Food and drinks available. Really good set-up for small kids too.
author: Riaan Grobler

text: Magic. Grab your cushions select your seats and you are ready to enjoy the show. Good hot food available. Wonderful local ice-cream in tub are must.
author: Russell Kenner

text: Had a great night watching Head South… with Q&A afterward with the director…Jonathan Ogilvie Glass of wine, some popcorn and a beautiful night…. Make for a memorable cinema experience… in my top 3!
author: Elwyn Davies JP

text: Love the vibe, the food and the view here ! I'll never forget all the lovely and kind staff ️ Thank u again for saving my nutrition container! Highly recommended! I'll definitely be back again next time I visit Darwin!️
author: ChunRu Yang

text: Rate: ⭐️⭐️⭐️⭐️⭐️ My friend and I visited Boatshed for the first time and were seriously impressed! We had the Eggs Benedict and Eggs Royale — both were absolutely delicious. The soft brioche was a standout and paired perfectly with everything. Coffee was spot-on, and the waterside seating with views of the boatyard made the experience even better. Toilets were clean too. Only downside was the long queue to order — took over 20 minutes and made the hallway a bit cramped. But surprisingly, our food and drinks came out within 5–10 minutes, and the staff were fantastic. You can bring your pet. Overall, 5/5. Will definitely be back! Suggestion: Add QR code ordering to speed things up and ease the congestion.
author: Nicole M

text: Breakfast was on our menu today. We ordered Bonnie Stack. Very nice. We loved the big coffee cups, so if coffee is your go-to, order one. They have a bin near the door with bread for feeding the fish near the jetty.
author: Suzanne Saxelby

text: Nice and cool place to dine during dry season. If you can’t finish your toast, take it down to the pier to feed the fish.
author: BeholdHim

text: Hands down the best food I have had since being in Darwin! The incredible staff, the atmosphere and the mouth watering food was all 10/10! Highly recommend ⭐️⭐️⭐️⭐️⭐️
author: Sarah Cutlack

text: Nightcliff Market is a great weekend spot to relax and enjoy time with family. There’s a nice mix of Aussie and Asian food, live music on some days, and a kids’ play area. Plenty of seating and a friendly vibe. You’ll find stalls selling handmade items, clothes, books, souvenirs, and some organic products. There are a few veggie stalls too, but not many. Easy to find parking and the bus stop is nearby. Worth a visit!
author: Emi Le

text: I visited the Nightcliff Markets while I was in Darwin and really enjoyed the vibe. They're on every Sunday from 8 am to 2 pm and run all year round. It’s a nice little market with a good mix of food stalls, arts and crafts, local produce, second-hand goods, and live music. It’s a more laid-back market compared to some of the busier ones around Darwin, but still has a great atmosphere. I had the most amazing fresh paw paw salad made right in front of me, and the mango juice with orange, ginger and honey was next level—so refreshing! Easily one of the best juices I’ve had:) Something to note—dogs aren’t allowed at the markets, which is the same across most of the markets in Darwin. It’s a bit of a shame if you're travelling with your dog, but worth knowing before you go. Parking can be a bit tight, but there’s usually some available around the shopping centre or nearby streets. If you’re in Darwin on a Sunday, it’s a great little spot to grab breakfast or lunch and enjoy some live music in a relaxed setting.
author: Happy Diane

text: Night cliff markets, open 8am-2pm Sat's & Sun's. We took the No.4 bus from Darwin CBD, 20min ride. We came in mid July & the weather was perfect- @ 30 degrees celcius & a nice breeze. A great market atmosphere, live music, huge array of centrally placed food vendors- lots of different food and drinks to try; laksa, tropical fruits juices, and LOTS more. Suitable for all ages groups. Market is mostly in shade. Toilet facilities and seating available all around market. Lovely stall of clothing, jewelery, books, homewares, touristy purchases. We then walked 20min flat ground walk over to nearby Rapid Creek Markets on roughly the same time (Sat/Sun mornings) which is more fresh produce based. Night cliff is a more general market and will have something to please everyone in the family. We would come to this market again
author: Louise Kean

text: Was a lovely experience. Jade with her healing herbs was of particular delight, a wonderful and insightful conversationalist and very pure soul who made my day and her wares were really great. I would also highly recommend trying the kangaroo tail nachos the lady working the stand there was also a very lovely person and the food was delicious, would highly recommend spending your Sunday morning here after Church.
author: Daniel M

text: Awesome markets to grab your yummy food, fresh fruit and vegetables and a piece of Aboriginal art for your family or friends. Relax with live music and enjoy your sunday mornings.
author: Vicki Bonson

text: A beautiful place to have a picnic, a short hike or for the kids to have a splash and cool off. There's lots of picnic tables, BBQs and quiet spaces to chill out under the shady trees. Clean and well kept with lots of parking and clean toilets. A wonderful place to spend the day, especially with interstate visitors. I highly recommend.
author: Jody Maguire

text: Howard Springs Nature Park is a great place to enjoy wildlife including turtles, barramundi, file snakes and freshwater fish species. You can cool off in a shallow series of man-made rock pools, let the kids enjoy the adventure playground and relax with a quiet picnic or barbeque. You can't swim in the spring-fed waterhole.
author: Anne & Mark

text: Nice spot for the kids. A small playground, some rock pools to splash in the spring with fish and turtles to see. An easy bush walk, picnic area all makes for a pleasant day out.
author: Pamela Rivers

text: Gorgeous place to visit for nature walks and to enjoy the tranquilty. Terrific pools, play equipment and waterfall for little kids and I found the military history interesting too.
author: Helen Wolfe

text: Lovely quiet spot. Great place for picnics! Has play equipment, fish feeding, water feature for kids, flying fox. There is also enough space that you can avoid people and enjoy some quiet time in nature reading a book. Tranquil, but fun. Good hiking trails and a spring.. It could do with a bit more love, I think. It would be great to see some swimming back at Howard Springs. Fish feeding pond looks pretty murky & heavy on algae, needs more fish to eat it? Birds were also very cute. It's definitely worth the short 20-minute drive. Lovely spot, would recommend for a visit. Take a picnic lunch.
author: Britt Wilson

text: This cruise was an absolute highlight of our holiday. One of the things that made it great was our indigenous guide. He was funny and interesting and it was fabulous hearing a bit about his and his family's way of life. The cruise was stunning. So many creatures to see and a gorgeous sunset. Highly recommend.
author: Kerry Pronk

text: After lunch cruise as part of day tour from Darwin on Sat 26/7/25 week ago. Cruise is about 1.5 hrs. The Skipper cum guide was excellent (did not get his name, sorry!) - gently swinging the boat around, so both sides got a turn to view the billabong's star attractions. Midway, he switched off the engines & allowed us to listen to the sounds of saltmarsh which was contemplative & tranquil. He was amusing, knowledgeable & imparted enough info without overwhelming. Apart from the Crocs, the birdlife is numerous. Watch the cutesy flitting of the pink crested Jacana & his little ones on the lilly pads, blue kingfisher darting in & out of the water, Darters drying their wings, tons of whistling ducks, elegant Jabirus, multitude of herons & some birds of prey flying overhead. Feral brumbies & introduced species also call this home & cannot be totally eradicated unfortunately. Just wished that I could stay longer to do both the sunrise & sunset cruise. There's plenty of cold water onboard to keep hydrated - stiflingly hot & humid. Spray/slather on your insect repellant before getting on. Master your mobile cam slow mo, zoom & shutter speed to get best shots. I struggled with mine but no matter, I enjoyed just observiing & being in the moment Loved it..️️
author: The Melbie

text: My friend and I took the sunrise cruise and had Scott as our guide. 10/10 experience! The weather started out cool and comfortable at 6.45am (it was already starting to get glaringly hot by 9am) and the morning light along the river was beautiful. But the highlight was the animals - we saw crocodiles up close and more variety of birds than we expected. Scott was a fountain of information with little quips we enjoyed plus there was ample time to take photos and listen to the tour. Would highly recommend to anyone!
author: Janice Chan

text: Absolutely fantastic tour, with Adam as operator. He has a deep, lived knowledge of his country and his passion for it shines through. Really impressive and the tour itself was breathtakingly beautiful too. Highly recommended.
author: Felix

text: Sunrise cruise, with Adam as our guide, was absolutely brilliant! Adam’s knowledge of Kakadu’s wildlife and fauna, traditional culture and climate impact was impressive and we loved his dry sense of humour. Plenty of birdlife, crocs and a sunrise that brought me to tears. An experience I’ll never forget.
author: Jo Elle

text: Today at the store entrance, a short-haired woman with glasses (the staff member holding the remote key) asked another staff member to check my bag. She looked unfriendly the whole time and showed no apology for this action. As a customer, I felt very uncomfortable and disrespected. I hope the supermarket can train their staff to handle such situations with more politeness and respect, instead of making customers feel offended.
author: To

text: Your eftpos was down. I rang to find out if it is back on and got a digital answering service that was unable to connect me to anyone. I suggest you pay a real person to talk to your customers
author: Max Alexander

text: Nice big shop, good fresh produce
author: Cathy Perrotta

text: Pretty clean store compared to the rest in darwin
author: Billie Johnson

text: Clean store had everything we needed
author: Chris

text: Great fun. Never too old to be a child. Grab a tube and bounce up and down with the waves. They’re pretty strong actually. Multiple lifeguards. They have lockers but bathrooms to change outside. Drink and snack stand. Waves start every 15 after and 15 till to give those a break to get in and out and just float or swim without the ups and downs.
author: Miss K

text: Really fun for the kids and adults alike! Staff are friendly, there are lockers inside the fenced area for a fee (self-serving and only big enough for small bags), lounge chairs and some bench seats. No toilets or change rooms inside, you have to leave and go to the toilets near the beach lagoon. Your entry fee is for the whole day, just keep your wrist band on. Waves are every 15 minutes and last 15 minutes. Super fun and you can bring your own ring tube. There's a kiosk for drinks and food. A nice day out.
author: Kim S

text: Darwin Wave Lagoon is a great place to visit. Waves come every 15 minutes and last for 15 minutes. The area is clean, spacious, and well-maintained. The staff is really friendly and supportive. We had a wonderful time and really enjoyed it!
author: Emi Le

text: We went for a dip on Saturday 15 February; unfortunately the wave machine wasn't working at 100% with repairs to be done on Monday 17 February *sad face* There were still waves, but they weren't as big as possible. Get to see the ladies "dive for a diamond" on Friday 14 February, A Hot 100 competition. They also hold water aerobics on Dunday mornings from the wave pool. Lost stars fue to repairs needing to be conducted.
author: Bernie Lea

text: Great way to chill out by the pool , plenty of space and there are lounge chairs with umbrellas. Kiosk has barista coffee machine, variety of cold drinks and snacks. Friendly staff too. Aqua fit on Sunday mornings are great way to start your Sunday.
author: Haz

text: The reception desk gave me documents relating to what we can do at Jabiru. The exhibits gave a further knowledge in the culture of the people around the region. The display boat was a good example of what can be built from barks of trees.
author: Jit Lim

text: To be honest the visitors centre was lovely but kakadu not so lovely. Nobody tells you when buying a park pass the park is virtually closed. All roads to the waterfalls and swimmable pools inaccessable. The lookouts are impaired by smoke haze due to the burn offs. Apparently June is the month they do the burn offs. So keep away that month. I understand these things can't be helped due to damage caused by the wet season and they have to do the burn off but at least let people know what's going on when purchasing a pass. The only closure we were aware of was gunlom falls which is due to open 4th July.
author: Pamela Rivers

text: Great setting and well laid out. Nice condition to throughout given the center’s age. Staff were friendly and of course had an an intimate and personal knowledge of the Park which was excellent. The museum section was great even though it was a little tired. The library was a hit with the kids allowing them to get some respite in the A/C while having some quiet reading time
author: Gee Whizz

text: Huge thank you to the lovely lady working Sunday 17 August in the morning. Was so helpful creating a doable route for us to see not only the places we had identified but others too. Wish I knew her name as she is great asset for the Visitors Centre.
author: Lynne Ali

text: The staff are very friendly and gives you great information about what and where to go for the camping, visiting or swimming. Give time to visit the Marrawuddi Gallery just tucked away behind, for great displays and information of the local culture. Well worth the half hour detour; longer if you want to use it as a break stop. The cafe is no longer there, but there’s still a filtered water dispenser (bring your own bottles) toilet facilities, tables, charging stations for laptops and mobile phones. The outdoor is peaceful and serene, for a picnic.
author: Serene Yeong

text: Where to even start?! Nitmiluk National Park is absolutely breathtaking. The sheer scale of the gorges, the rugged cliffs, and the peaceful Katherine River winding through it all make this place unforgettable. Every corner feels like a postcard – whether you’re cruising along the river, hiking one of the many trails, or simply taking in the views. It’s not just the scenery, but the sense of history and culture here that makes it so special. The connection to the Jawoyn people is deeply felt, and it adds such richness to the experience. This park is a true Northern Territory gem – wild, stunning, and completely awe-inspiring. A must-see for anyone visiting the Top End.
author: Nakita Nia

text: Nitmiluk National Park is an unforgettable stop—we camped there for three nights and had an amazing time exploring the region. We went hiking, kayaking through the stunning gorges, and even tried to spot freshwater crocs (no luck, but still a thrill!). The landscapes are breathtaking and the park is well set up for visitors. Highly recommended for anyone looking to experience the Top End’s natural beauty.
author: teo nguyen

text: Cruised through an ancient gorge system. These sandstones in the Katherine Gorge are 1600 million years old. Very sweaty and lots of flies. But still worth the 7 - hour drive overnight trip from TC. P. S. Where the 2007 Rogue crocodile movie was shot and the final pitstop of the Amazing Race Australia 2019.
author: Maricar Peralta

text: Enjoyed my time at the park. Nice walks and water holes to see.
author: Pamela Rivers

text: What a great spot and the sunset dinner cruise was out of this world !!!
author: Tony Fogarty

text: Shelves are empty very regularly also very frequently stocked with wrong items staff have just pushed other items to the side to unload their cartons to save them having to take them back out to the warehouse section things are often in the wrong section just for example today no Chinese greens at all on display just filled up with cos lettuce must have had some left in box and just shoved them in there this is consistent problem with this supermarket last 12 months would love to go in there and sort it all out not hard. all casual staff d couldn’t care less there a week or so and how. Permanent staff do their best management totally incompetent last 12 months no milk no bread some days etc am told veggies and meat tossed outvon a regular basis as not put out lucky there are not more supermarkets close by
author: Bob Blanch

text: For a relatively small store, they had most of what we were looking for. Clean, neat, tidy and well laid out. Eay to shop here and relatively easy to park.
author: Geoff Wood

text: The worst Woolworths I have ever frequented. Consistently keeping desired and high selling products off the shelf in order to move less wanted items. Items considered ordinary such as ice berg lettuce are unavailable for days on end (just the latest such example). When attending this Woolworths shopping lists are mere hope lists. Rarely does one exit the store with all the items they intended to purchase. To add insult to this incompetence the shopper is treated with behaviour bordering on hostility. As close to a Soviet shopping experience as an Australian in the 21st century is likely to find.
author: Hercules Rockefeller

text: Hey yall, I went here yesterday on 18/07/2027 and all I can say is this place is so much worse then coles not only did the staff not help me buy the correct natural deodorant that i use for my anus but they told me to just wait. 20 MINIUTES later and my anus starts to smell and now im embarised because my soon to be wife regan barret is not copmplementing my sent
author: Lewis Comtrado

text: I have been there just now, main purpose to buy some 2 litres fresh milk. The shelf was empty. So, i asked a team member (Longlife, forgot the name), he already finished his work but called fresh dept twice in 5 minutes interval. No one came. Waited 15-20 minutes. Then asked a guy from online (Ramesh) and he helped me to get the milks from back. So, Thank you Ramesh. Genuine customer service here and helping attitude towards the customers. He should get rewarded from the store manager for his good attitude. Thanks a lot.
author: Pratik Debnath

text: Fabulous place to stay. We were on a powered site and our friends were in a accessible cabin. Staff are so helpful and cheerful. Camp kitchen, bbq and laundry areas well maintained. Refreshing new swimming pool as well as the original pool. Even a fire pit set up waiting to be used. Cabin was spacious and serviced regularly during our friends stay. Thoroughly recommended
author: Lyn Koehne

text: A beautiful oasis. The caravan park is just beautiful. Spotless amenities and some of the most friendliest staff you will come across in the NT. Stunning location near the beautiful beach just a shame you can’t swim in it. The pub is right next to the park and is fantastic. It offers cold beers, great food, friendly staff and beautiful views.
author: Leah Cooke

text: We had 4 groups and I booked them incorrectly, Naomi and team went above and beyond to sort our group out and have us all next to each other, in ensuite sites - which was fabulous! Amenities & pools are meticulously maintained, camp kitchen was beautiful and so clean! Very impressed with the crab cooker!
author: Susanne Carter

text: Had a great stay here. We took unpowered site down the back which was great away from everyone. Had trees to shade us from afternoon sun too. All their amenities we could fault. Close to the tavern (great) and beach.
author: Robyn Jeffery

text: Great facilities and location with the Dundee Beach Tavern right adjacent. Kids loved the pool and fishing off the jetty for sharks at night with a few locals. Be careful of the resident 4 metre crocodile that is often seen near the beach.
author: Scott McGuigan

text: Stayed on a powered site which was nice and big, bit dusty but this is dry season in NT. Dog friendly site and can get them in the outside area when its quite. Toilets and showers are lacking maintenance and the hard water is not kind to the pipework but this is a remote bush camp. Hot Springs are nice and were not as hot as we expected, bats are everywhere and are a sight to see. Would definitely come back.
author: Chris Fletcher

text: Stayed two nights payed for power and water on a caravan site but we were lucky if we got water and when we did it dribbled out. Luckily our tanks in the caravan were full so we could use our own water. In the two days we were there the amenities did not get cleaned. The toilets were absolutely disgusting. The staff weren’t friendly horrible place to stay. The springs were nice but that’s it. Would not recommend staying there.
author: Tricia Clavey

text: Great location but that’s about it, paid for a powered site with water but the pressure was so poor it took 8 minutes to fill a caravan sink so we had no chance of using our shower but luckily for us we were only 40 meters from the amenities block that I wish I didn’t have to use as it was absolutely terrible, the place was filthy with locks missing from 40% of the showers and toilets doors. It’s such a shame that this has been let go to get to this sad state of disrepair, will I come back to stay probably not and that’s such a shame as it is a great location
author: Neil Backhouse

text: The setting is peaceful and the food and entertainment were good. BUT Amenities block disgusting. I don’t mind “old” but the sinks and toilets could do with a good scrub. The water pressure abysmal and must be costing a fortune as most site taps were leaking. $$$ made each day so maintenance shouldn’t be this bad.
author: Susanne Pedler

text: The thermal springs were lovely but accommodation leaves a lot to be desired. We would not recommend staying in the cabins and was told by woman at check in when asked about going into a motel room that they were worse!!! Our cabin was pretty disgusting! The only positive thing I can say is that the sheets looked clean. Two windows with vertical blinds had so many slats missing there was no privacy!! Someone did come and moved slats to one window and then hung a curtain on the other when we complained. The oven, hot plates and surrounds were disgustingly filthy and the oven didn’t work! No plug for the kitchen sink so had to wash up with running water! The shower and hand basins were very grubby! Cupboard doors broken or missing! We were continually throwing out food or spraying because of ants! Will never be back!
author: Rhonda

text: NT Oriental Emporium is a popular Asian grocery store in Darwin offering a wide variety of products from different countries across Asia. The store has a spacious layout, making shopping comfortable, and even includes a cozy coffee area at the back. Conveniently located, it’s easy to access by both bus and car.
author: Emi Le

text: I really enjoy shopping at NT Oriental Emporium! They have such an amazing selection of Asian groceries, and the prices are super competitive. I think they probably have the widest variety of noodles around, which is a huge plus! Every time I step into the store, I'm excited by the vast selection of ingredients, snacks, drinks, teas, spices and instant meals available- it's truly a one-stop shop for all your needs. The staff are always friendly and extremely helpful, which makes every visit a great experience. I highly recommend NT Oriental Emporium to anyone looking to stock up on quality Asian products!
author: Areej

text: After reading the reviews, I was quite excited to do my Asian grocery shopping for the first time at NT emporium. Sadly, I was quite disappointed with the limited variety of options. The prices are quite high and yes the store is nice and clean and has big space with friendly staff but I expected to see more fresh produce like fresh egg noodles, fresh chilies, garlic, ginger, coriander, bean sprouts, etc. even the sauce selections are limited (no Sriracha sauce!). Some items are more expensive than Woolies Asian section (dry noodles). I had a list of items I wanted to buy and expected to pay over $100 for my first shop, however only 1/3 of my list was filled and i spent no where near $100.
author: Beau Beau

text: Possibly the best Asian food market in Darwin. They have something for everyone. We always come back with a full bag after each visit. Visit at least a few times per month to get staple food, noodles, drinks, snacks etc. Very clean and large store. Friendly staff who can help you find food that you don't know the name of but can describe it or show photos of. There's even some European food on offer. A bit tricky to reach when being guided by the GPS sometimes as it wants you to make a u-turn in strange locations. Better have a look at the map and turn into the smaller road "De Latour Street" and enter from that road instead of trying to reach it straight from "Bagot Road".
author: Robin Eriksson

text: NT Oriental Emporium is hands down one of the best Asian grocery stores in Darwin! The shop is quite spacious and well-organised, offering an impressive selection of Asian products—from fresh produce and snacks to spices, sauces, and specialty ingredients that are often hard to find elsewhere. What truly sets this place apart is the exceptional customer service. The staff are friendly, welcoming, and always happy to help. During our visit, they even extended their closing hours just to let us finish shopping at our own pace—such a rare and thoughtful gesture! If you're looking for a well-stocked Asian supermarket with great service, this is the place to go. Highly recommended!
author: Mike Kamali

text: Great Park to stay, has everything you need and want and more. We originally booked for 8 nights and ended up staying 15 nights. Mark was a fabulous host and was willing help when needed. Coffee van in the park was a winner, friendly folk and great coffee and yummy cookies. Ensuite style amenities are a winner for me! Pools are fabulous, camp kitchen well set up. Our site had lovely green grass, was well shaded and close to everything in the park. Pet Friendly and had a Dog Sitter 2 streets away at a great price. It was an easy straight run into Darwin from here also. I would definitely recommend this park!! Steve & Rhonda
author: Rhonda McCormick

text: I am writing to share the profoundly negative experience we had upon our arrival. We reached the reception desk at 5:03 PM precisely, only to be met with immediate hostility from the woman in charge. Before we could even explain our situation, she shouted at us that the reception was closed. We calmly tried to explain that we were in an emergency situation, hoping for a shred of understanding or assistance. Instead, we were met with a complete refusal to even consider a solution. There was no discussion, no flexibility, and certainly no compassion. Working in the tourism and hospitality industry requires a fundamental appreciation for human contact and a capacity for empathy. The individual we encountered possessed neither. Her behaviour was not just unprofessional; it was deeply unkind. One has to wonder about the kind of life that leads to such a cold and dismissive attitude towards people in need. I genuinely suggest she reconsiders her career path, as she is clearly unsuited for any role that requires customer service. This was a truly shocking and disheartening welcome.
author: Sébastien Prevel

text: Loved the caravan park, the staff were helpful and friendly. We had a great site, the peacocks were very friendly, as was the little possum who visited us a couple of nights. We felt safe and secure there. They have a coffee van on site and offered Cambodian street food on the Saturday night. We used our own facilities so I can't comment on theirs. The only negative comment I would make is about the boom gates - they are very slow, the entry pin pad is very loose and wobbles about, and the exit boom gate took absolutely ages to lower when the car in front had gone through. So we spent more time than necessary at the boom gates. Other than that - we loved our stay there - it wasn't far from all the places we had planned to visit during our visit to Darwin.
author: NL

text: Our second visit to Darwin but first in this park. We love Darwin. And we thoroughly enjoyed our stay at this Big4. The staff were incredibly friendly and helpful, we had a great roomy site. Whilst we did not swim, the pools both looked very inviting. Enjoyed the company if the resident peacocks with my morning yoga.
author: Glenda BROWN (The Browns)

text: We booked a 2 bedroom cabin with a queen bed in one bedroom and a double and single bunk upon arrival I noticed only the queen bed was made up with bed sheets and not the other bedroom, I rang them to tell them and their response was there's only 2 of you, and I said but I booked a 2 bedroom and would like the beds to be made up ,not very happy to oblige but made up bed which took a lot of effort, looked at me and thought about it and her response was "are you sleeping separately and my reply YES ! I should not have to explain my sleeping arrangements with them but was told that I should have notified them which I think it's ridiculous , so infact had I paid for a 2 bedroom and was expected to sleep in one bedroom. In that case I would have booked only 1 bedroom cabin , not sleep in one bedroom and pay for 2 bedroom, and there was the bathroom towel issue only 2 bath towels no hand towels of face washers. asked if I could have hand towels only given one I said can I have another one as there is 2 of us looked at me as this was a big effort on her behalf to get me another hand towel. I mention to her that we have stayed there before about 4 years ago and did not have this problem with the towels or the bedroom lined. was told that it has always been that way I think not ! We have stayed at other Big 4 s and in a 2 bedroom cabin towes supplied on all beds and bed linen in all regardless weather slept on of not. Bottom line is we booked and paid for a 2 bedroom. The cabins need a lot of work looking very run down holes in walls and uncomfortable , could have at least a 2 seater couch in them sitting on plastic chairs is not great. I would not recommend this caravan park for cabin use, if you book for a 2 bedroom make sure the beds are all made up and bath towels supplied. A very disappointed stay this time.
author: Stephen Pallone

text: I’d waited all of August to be able to visit here with my daughter, got the dog in the kennels at Helgas and off we went. It was such a great visit, on a hot early September day. The car park wasn’t at all packed as it was late in the season but still quite a few people swimming and BBQing, having a great time. The walk up and over the falls is nice, a bit steep but gets you warmed up even more so you’re ready for the cool pool and water falls. We swam all the way around the pool to the falls, so lovely. And fenced off from crocs being able to get in, I think it’s checked regularly as well. A must visit
author: Paul Tooze (No Journey Too Small)

text: Wangi Falls is one of the most impressive spots in Litchfield — the scale of the twin waterfalls is absolutely stunning and took my breath away the moment I saw it. The plunge pool is large and deep, and while swimming across to the base of the falls is a bit of a workout, it’s well worth it. Pool noodles are highly recommended, even for confident swimmers, to help float and fully enjoy the experience. There’s a short walking trail nearby through a forested area, where we spotted bats sleeping upside down in the trees — some still awake and making quite a bit of noise, which added to the atmosphere. For those not planning to swim, there’s also a fantastic viewing platform overlooking the falls. The amenities here are excellent — the cafe (though closed when we arrived mid-afternoon) and the modern, clean toilets and change rooms were better than most other stops in the park. Just keep an eye out for a few orb-weaver spiders near the walking paths. All in all, a must-visit stop in Litchfield — both beautiful and well set up for a comfortable, memorable experience.
author: Helen Nguyen

text: Beautiful, very easy access to get there. Steps into water. At about 5pm, Friday, we were the only ones there. Very beautiful
author: mia Wells

text: TheNomad.family enjoyed doing the loop walk and having a dip at the Wangi Falls. Lots of wildlife there. Rainforest walk is amazing. Many flying foxes on the treetops.
author: Peter - TheNomad.family

text: Beautiful spot for a swim and picnic as it’s shaded, has grass, BBQ’s and toilets. It even has a cafe! Easy access down to falls so perfect for everyone.
author: Krystle

text: So so impressed by the team. Had a detailed itinerary ready, but went through with a team member who clarified everything, suggested changes - and confirmed what was/wasn’t open. They recommended particular activities/falls that ended up being the clear highlights of our trip. This is such an asset to NT tourism and really makes you feel safe as a tourist with crocodile safety etc. Even if you’re confident - just walk in and run your plans by them - you won’t regret it!
author: GC

text: Staff were great, loved the hopon hop off bus museum was great, the restaurant on the wharf best freshest oysters and service in darw
author: Angela Todd

text: Definitely go to Top End Visitor Information Centre for car rental. They offer a genuine 25% off rates. We hired an MG SUV for A$52! Shane was our agent and he was super-helpful too with maps and suggested directions. Litchfield National Park is your “must see”. Drive the loop from Batchelor to Berry Springs (in that direction).
author: Stephen Asbury

text: Everything you need to know about the NT is here. Only thing they could do better is more staff as I waited over 20 minutes for simply a city map as they had none to simply collect on entry.
author: ROBERT ARC

text: If I could give a zero rating I would. Received false information about the status of Kakadu attractions being open and subsequently spent about $1000 and 2 days of wasted time because most things were not accessible. Outrageous!
author: Davina Duffy

text: As everyone else has said, the sunsets are stunning! Especially when a bush fire has put some smoke in front of the setting sun. There’s a good car park, BBQ’s and toilets in the reserve before the beach. The beach is massive with the sea going out a long way. You should watch out for crocodiles near the shore but the chances of one being there is remote. But could be!
author: Paul Tooze (No Journey Too Small)

text: Beautiful sunset. Good place to relax and enjoy the view.
author: Johan Barrington

text: Lee Point Beach is a serene oasis in Darwin, offering tranquility like no other. It's the exclusive spot to witness the breathtaking sunrise over the ocean at dawn. The peaceful ambiance here is perfect for a tranquil escape from the bustling city life. The gentle waves and golden sands create a picturesque setting for a leisurely stroll or simply unwinding by the water. Whether you're a nature enthusiast or seeking a serene sunrise experience, Lee Point Beach is the ultimate destination. Don't miss the chance to start your day with the sun's first rays painting the sky in vibrant hues over this quiet, coastal gem.
author: Ares RS

text: I was there on a low tied and the water retracts far back on the low so I had lots of beach to explore. Amazing colors in the water and sky. Storm brewing in distant horizon. Just spectacular!!
author: david

text: A great place for bird and nature nerds like myself. However be prepared for sandflys and mosquitos with insect repellent. In dry season it's a great hangout for walks, wildlife wonder and beautiful beaches (no swimming unless you want to come up close and personal with a saltwater crocodile.... definitely not recomended... always be .) Also there is a bird hide for shorebird season, coming up soon in Darwin. Sunset gazing, and rock hole exploring is viable. In build up it can feel very challenging but then in wet season it is also magical. Bring your binoculars but leave your dog at home. From the point east it is a no doggy area. Hopefully nature lovers like myself around the world will be able to from the bulldozers so we can truly call Darwin home to some great nature.
author: Betty Bird

text: Great place to take a picnic, relax and watch the sun set
author: Justyn Walcott

text: Had lunch at the boat shed. Good food, reasonably priced. Great location. Skye loved the harbour
author: Tina Hart

text: I just want to stay there. Very pleasant indeed. Just a hop and a skip from downtown Darwin. A beer or wine by the marina or maybe a meal, before or after a spin around the bay on the ferry. Lovely.
author: Neil Hawkes

text: A good marina tucked in behind Fannie Bay. It's an extensive area with shops and plenty of restaurants as well as apartments. The marina appears to be well kept. If you are sailing into the marina, you will need to call ahead to ensure they have space for your yacht. Plus, you will need to enter via a lock. If you miss the lock hours, it's easy to moor in the bay or near the channel. I'm not sure about yachty facilities as I didn't need to use them. I would suggest they need to sort out their rubbish disposal options. There are lots of dining options, and it's a great spot to go and watch the sunset on the grassy bank above the beach.
author: MN K

text: From the marina, one can appreciate the view of the lovely houses and boats. There are many walking areas around the marina, leading down to the beach where you can witness a beautiful sunset.
author: Areej

text: Normally I don’t like doing a review for anything because I do business and been working for many jobs as a customer service. Also I used to work for Woolworth before. On Wednesday the 4th June 2025. I finished work late and took my mum out for shopping at Casuarina Woolies at 7:30pm. I understand that is less front staff and more to nightfill and grocery staff working. We got ready to check out with small trolly pretty much small and big stuffs. But there are non service open, only small desk serve and self service. So I have experience I decided to go for the self service. As you know Woolies have small space for putting scanned item on the side and is not allow if the item doesn’t put on side after you scanned and the machine is stuck for assistant. So I asked one lady to help me with the quantity so is easier and faster, but she standing doesn’t want to help and ask me to scan one by one. Then I told her to I couldn’t cause is full on the side. So I have 12 pack mince beef and she’s play a game count twice and twice, so I said come on I’m rushing home I don’t have time to wait for you counting just 12 pack beef, but rest of all item I did scanned myself. She gave me that face and told me you should come early and do your shopping. And smash damage my item on the side and my mum was so mad and argue that we not gonna pay $300 for the shopping that she’s doing like a rubbish. And she’s pointing at me that I am rude to her that I asked her to help with quantity that she doesn’t want to help at that time. She said I was rude to ask her to rush. Oh well if I ask the customer service staff to count twice and twice for just 12 pack beef would anyone wait for her? And I have repeated to her and is only 12 pack on the trolly nothing else. One thing I know for customer service. If you don’t want to work and you’re tired from the long day. Don’t put your mood on someone who didn’t do anything wrong to you. And if you cannot handle this PLEASE STAY HOME and relax how you like. I have right to go shopping whenever is still open. If I can scanned without needing permission from assistance I don’t want to ask anyone of those shit staff to help me. Thanks
author: Anothai Janthajaem

text: This post is about the products at Woolworths. As someone who commonly shops at Woolies and Cole’s, I can tell there’s a huge quality difference. Everytime I purchase a monster from Woolworth’s I find it’s flat or tastes off somehow, but Cole’s tastes fresh and as it should? It’s the same products so there shouldn’t be a difference correct? Just today I bought a pack of burger rings from Woolworth’s and hadn’t realised that I already bought one from Cole’s earlier in the week. Opened the Woolworth’s ones, tasted stale and old, so I closed it up and ate the Cole’s ones, fresh and could have been made yesterday from the way they tasted. I understand stock rotation and the fact oldest products go to the front new to the back, but it’s such a consistent decline in quality when comparing Cole’s and Woolworth’s..? I don’t know why this seems to be the case, whether Cole’s staff just choose not to rotate so fresh product goes first, but it’s always better.
author: Melissa C

text: I barely post a review but the lady who checked out for me today was so rude. She is middle aged with glasses on. She didn’t say hi, nothing, just scan and didn’t even ask if I had my everyday card until I told her and then that’s it. NO thank you in the end. The only thing i heard from her was “receipt?” 1* for this kind of customer service.
author: Huong Le

text: The layout of the store is good and the shelves are always stocked well - a few weeks ago, they always had eggs when Coles had run out. The staff are friendly and helpful.
author: Bernie Lea

text: Today 27th March 2024, I visited Woolworths at Casuarina Square 0810 with my 6-month-old son and my wife. Everything is good until we reach the self-service checkout. There is a staff lady with no badge name on her uniform, she has black short hair and wearing glasses, who asked me to open my nappy bag and check. I know that is a usual rule at every retail provider. I already opened my nappy bag for her to check. There is no problem at all. However, after checking my bag, I asked her name as I did not see it on her uniform. Then she started to scream and she called security and the store manager to come. She keeps saying "You are not allowed to ask my name". We feel like we are a crime. Moreover, when she saw I was holding my phone in my hand, she thought I was taking her photo and she again screamed "You are not allowed to take my picture". After that, I explained everything to the store manager that her customer service was really bad and I already shown my phone to the security man and the store manager that I did not take any of her photos. She was so angry and aggressive just because I asked her name. This is so an awful experience us for when shopping at Woolies. The store manager then said sorry to us and she said her name is Joseline/Josephine. I used to work in Casuarina Square and I heard a lot of people complain about her. But this is the first time I have had this experience. I know I need to make this complaint about Josephine/Joseline. If she keeps that bad behaviour to customers, everyone will choose another store to shop at. This is the first time I gave 1 star on a shop/store. If I can gave 0 star, I will do that.
author: Henry

text: We enjoyed a very pleasant walk on the pathway near Casuarina Drive with views out over Beagle Gulf and onto the Tiwi Islands. The beach is very popular and is also quite beautiful with clear waters & a number of outstanding rock features including Cheryl‘s rock and some rock carving up towards the end. There are a couple of coffee shops on this walk as well.
author: Ross Daniels

text: One of the best places in Darwin to watch sunset. Great area for running and dog friendly beach. Highly recommend coming down for Sunset while you're in Darwin 🫶
author: Amogh Manandhar

text: I lived in Nightcliff for 16 years and my family and I spent many days playing on Nightcliff beach. The sunsets are truly magical I don't recommend swimming as there are crocodiles around, but when the tide goes out there's lots of little pools of shallow water the kids can splash in. It's a great place for a family picnic or a romantic stroll on the beach. There's usually food vans along the Nighcliff foreshore most days making it a great place to grab a meal and watch the sunset. Plenty of picnic tables and electric BBQs available and public toilets at various locations along the foreshore.
author: Jody Maguire

text: I'm loving the view and the vibes here. It seems so peaceful here.
author: Jenny Wu

text: I've thoroughly enjoyed swimming and spending time on this beach. Nightcliff is a great place to stay.
author: Helen Wolfe

text: Beautiful sunset views from our balcony. Bed is comfortable and air-conditioning very welcome. Lovely and quiet at night. No hairdryer in room but can be requested. Toaster & microwave & some kitchen utensils in the cupboard. Overall a very good setup. Constructive suggestions; some hooks in the bathroom &/or another towel rail are needed. The curtains are very dirty on the balcony side too. But, thank you for a great stay.
author: Barbara M

text: We had our room upgraded, which was pleasant and gave us a lot more space. Staff were very helpful and nice, including the housekeeping team. Views from the balcony were fantastic and the room had all comfort. The nearby Cullen Bay precinct at the forefront is clean and very enjoyable On the flip side the room is outdated and in need of a little refurbishment and the undercover parking is a little tight, but there is plenty more outside at the back. Recommended
author: kitchen team

text: These resort apartments are privately owned, and then you book which apartment is wanted. Some are so so and others beautiful. We had an average apartment, but it serviced. Curtains and some walls were dirty and dust hanging off popcorn ceilings. The air conditioning vents were not clean. Very basic kitchen facilities provided and beware there is NO hairdryer. The bed was clean and comfy, but pillows were not the best. Great pool area with BBQ , and the view from the waterside rooms was spectacular. There are great restaurants in the bay, too.
author: rosfryfry Fry

text: Three of us stayed there & found the 2 bedroom apartment spacious & well equipped. Loved the gorgeous marina views. It was easy to get around by foot & bus. Lovely helpful staff. Shop looked well stocked with useful groceries but we didnt need to do any shopping. Undercover carpark was a bonus when we had a rental car.
author: Lucy Tsun

text: My daughter booked this apartment for us as we are over from England. She asked for ajoining rooms and a good view and that is exactly what we got. They were quick to come and unlock the 2 rooms for access and we asked for a clothes airer and that was brought to our room within 5 mins. There is a free bus into the city centre and a 5 min walk to the marina where you can get something to eat and drink. 10 mins gets you to the market on Mindil beach, a great sunset there also. There is a washing machine, tumble dryer, microwave, cooker, kettle and fridge. They provide 2 sachets of washing powder and washing up liquid to get you started . There is a balcony with 2 chairs and 2 small swimming pools. There are fans and air con in both the bedroom and living room a well as a tv in both rooms.
author: sharon noyes

object: Banyan Tree caravan park resort Litchfield
text: Quintessential northern territory. The owners of this place are a genuine family, Mum Dad and five kids. And they all take part in running the place. It was wonderful. The setting was sublime and the service and attention was great. The pizza we had was one of the best pizzas we've had in the northern territory, and the buffalo burger was excellent as well. Great food and good live music to accompany after happy hour. Yes I would come back to this one again.
author: Christopher Moad

object: Banyan Tree caravan park resort Litchfield
text: What an absolute gem of a place with big shady caravan sites, beaut amenities and a pool. The new owners are fantastic and all of the family are extremely friendly. With 'on tap' beer that is deliciously cold and a nice selection of wines etc. The burgers were pretty good and the pizza's looked great. Plus live music. All of this less than an hours drive of some beautiful swimming holes in Litchfield NP. We would definately stay again. Well done Banyan Tree .
author: Kim Hayward

object: Banyan Tree caravan park resort Litchfield
text: New owners had just taken over 3 days before we arrived. Made us feel very welcome. Happy hour at the bar between 5-6pm. We had a pizza and and a couple of bowls of chips. Very good. Beer, cider and Ginger Beer on tap. Amenities were clean and maintained. Beautiful park surroundings. Powered and non powered sites. Plenty of shaded areas. Although you looked like you were under the pump. You guys did a great job. Thanks from all of us... Good luck in the future...
author: Mark Palmer

object: Banyan Tree caravan park resort Litchfield
text: I had a great stay at Banyan Tree Resort — a relaxed, laid-back caravan park with a welcoming vibe. The cabins were clean, comfortable. Lovely shower, hot with great water pressure. Bring your own soap! The location is super convenient, close to some beautiful local waterholes, making it perfect for exploring the area. The on-site restaurant is open for lunch and dinner, offering a small but delicious menu. Overall, a great place to unwind and enjoy the natural surroundings. Highly recommend!
author: tammy boland

object: Banyan Tree caravan park resort Litchfield
text: Their hospitality is top-notch.The staffs went above and beyond to make us feel welcome, just like true blue Aussies do. The place itself is a beauty, with super clean and lush green surroundings that make you feel right at home with nature. It's a proper peaceful escape. And let's talk about the tucker – absolutely delish! Every meal was a winner, proper yummy grub that hit the spot. Plus, they had live music which was a fantastic touch, creating a brilliant atmosphere for kicking back and relaxing. They’ve got a lovely children’s python on site as well ! It is quite a sight to see and added a quirky, memorable element to our stay. All in all, if you're looking for a cracking spot with great food, awesome tunes, a friendly vibe, and a bit of unique wildlife, the Banyan Tree Resort & Caravan Park is the place to be. Highly recommend it!
author: Brendan Hart

text: Thank you to Andy for an amazing Sunrise Tour on the 5th of August 2025! An amazing experience! And he was so nice even though I drive a JetSki like a nana, 10/10 highly recommended and would do again! ️
author: Paige Hiestand

text: I done the 3pm Die Another Day tour it was unbelievable and the guide Andy was unbelievable very very good at his job highly recommend just clad I didn't see the crocodile
author: brian patterson

text: I had the most stunning morning on the sunrise jet ski tour. I’d never ridden a jet ski but Andy and Darren were so fun, explained it all and it was 10/10. A must in Darwin. Best way to start your day.
author: Victoria Ginzburg

text: Andy paid me a lot of money to say how great a tour guide he was.. Joking aside Andy was a cracking tour guide and really went the extra sea mile to give us an awesome time. Thank you! We did the Espresso Martini tour
author: D

text: Absolutely 10/10 – highly recommend! Had the best time out on the water with 00Seven Jet Ski. Helena was an incredible guide and made the whole experience super fun and relaxed. Whether you're a local (like me) or just visiting Darwin, this is a must-do! Helena made such a great point during the tour — we’re usually standing on the shore looking out at the ocean, but seeing Darwin from the water gives you a whole new perspective. The views were stunning, and the ride itself was such a thrill. Will definitely be booking again!
author: Brandon

text: Good size Coles. Good supply of Fruit and Vege. Some items didn't have prices on the shelves so skipped those items. Returned and was overcharged on an item. The lady pulled to price tag and explained we couldn't have the item at the advertised special. We got a full refund on the item
author: JASON WILLIAMS

text: Great staff over the years however today I met Peter a manager, well manager material he is not. Rude arragant is to good for this man. Guys on the deli and girls on the front end where awsome
author: Wendy Shinnick

text: Shelves completely bare and this isn’t because trucks got stuck - just lazy staff, people standing around doing nothing. Do yourself a favour and go to Woolies across the road.
author: Georgie Mumford

text: So clean and my local store but PLEASE can you have hot chickens for dinner? Rarely availabke after 4pm.
author: Terese Bretag

text: Friendly staff, my local store and I love to shop here!!
author: Laurie M15

text: A park land area with some gardens and fountains. There were restroom but I didn't use them so can't comment on condition. The play ground was receiving some attention to the shade sails at the time and looked like most kids would be entertained for a while.
author: Itisi Memyself

text: Got off the plane in Darwin and drove the kids straight to this playground (5 mins by car). They absolutely loved it, missus and I enjoyed a nice walk around the ponds and fountains. The place is lush and well maintained, playground was pretty cool too.
author: Rob

text: Nice area for a walk with playground and picnic facilities. Be mindful there may be intoxicated itinerants at times so take normal safety precautions. There are artificial ponds and the natural rapid creek alongside.
author: Pini Achive

text: Best kept secret relaxing peaceful nature park for kids with great water fountain. Walking distance from bus stop No.10 & 4. Located behind the skateboard park, safe kid cycling area, clean kid playing area.
author: Brightone Nik

text: nice area for walking. there's a nearby barbecue and tables, with a playground for kids. surprised not more people go there.
author: Shaina Villaroza

text: An awesome evening, the hosts were amazing and friendly, the service impeccable, the food was of a very high standard. Lovely cool evening finishing with a light show from Mother Nature. Thank you for a wonderful dinner cruise, I highly recommend.
author: Elizabeth McKinlay

text: An unforgettable experience! The cruise offered fresh, locally sourced meals that tasted absolutely amazing. Enjoying such high-quality food while watching a stunning sunset from the boat made it even more special. The service was fantastic—attentive, friendly, and warm—which really added to the relaxed and welcoming atmosphere onboard. Highly recommended for anyone wanting a beautiful evening out on the water.
author: Ryan Locke

text: My husband and I had a wonderful sunset cruise experience with Murno and his fantastic team on Cape Adieu. This cruise exceeded our expectations - lovely sunset, friendly and attentive crew, a personalised approach with our table and the best 4 course meal we've enjoyed in ages with fresh seafood and tender steak included. We highly recommend this cruise to anyone wanting that something special from the Darwin Harbour.
author: Tracey Lowe

text: Unforgettable experience for the whole family! We all thoroughly enjoyed the Cape Adieu Sunset Dinner Cruise—it was the perfect way to take in Darwin’s iconic sunset. The atmosphere was relaxed, the food was delicious, and the views were absolutely stunning. A special shout-out to Pip and Gracie who were our graciousn hosts for the evening—so friendly and attentive! Even showed my daughter around the boat! Highly recommend this experience for anyone visiting Darwin. Thank you Munro and Grace
author: L Bar

text: What an experience! We celebrated our wedding anniversary on board and it was amazing from the food to the drinks all was 10/10. My dietary requirements were met and they went above and beyond to ensure this was noted on our sheet so everyone knew! We will be back again likely with family.
author: Emma Murphy

text: Water slides have not been working since February which is difficult to entertain older children as the smaller pool area is suited to younger children and toddlers. Engagement regarding the lightning process is important. Communication about this policy and how far away the lightning is and how long it precludes users of the park to enjoy the water play is very important. For a three hour birthday party, we could only spend one hour in two intervals in the water. Please fix the water slides.
author: Sharon Gardiner

text: This place is fantastic! My 4yo & 2yo had a wonderful time playing in the splash park. The grounds are really well maintained and lifeguards are on duty. Plenty of shady areas to set up. Toilet facilities with large change area is very handy. I still can't believe that it's free entry!
author: Karen Bergersen

text: Great park. I can't really complain when it's free But in saying that, they really need to upgrade the mats for the speed slides. They are falling apart. They would have got 5 stars if the mats were in better condition.
author: Colin Cutler

text: It was quiet for a Public Holiday. The last time we visited was 2 years ago and the place look different, different but better now. My 12 year old, husband and I enjoy the big slides while my 2 year old enjoy the water park. Good place for a family outing.
author: Elsie Legaspi

text: This place is pretty much out of commission atm. The kiosk is never open and the slides/splash pad are closed. It's ok if you just want to take a toddler to the shaded small pool otherwise just drive to leanyer instead.
author: Green Machine

text: Massive Rave to Lloyd our bus driver and tour guide, and to Dylan our boat guide and driver. Both of these guys had excellent entertainment skills and were very knowledgeable! Our family of four thoroughly enjoyed ourselves. Highly recommend to anyone wanting to go do this. 10/10
author: Natasha Roberts

text: Had an amazing time Lloyd our tour guide on the bus gave us the best Australian experience and his local knowledge is superb! The boat telluride with Skipper Jake was sensational! To say we saw the cross up close and personal is an understatement! Highly recommended, a must do.
author: Sam Keim

text: We had an awesome time! Both Lloyd (our driver) and Jake (boat captain) were very informative and funny, made the trip very enjoyable. They are obviously people with passion! But of course the real stars were all the crocodiles on the river - they are intimidating and impressive at the same time. If u have a free day at Darwin I really recommend this trip - it's 4-5hrs so I won't exhaust you, but u'll be able to really experience the wild nature from up close.
author: Bartosz Podlipniak

text: Lloyd was an amazing tour driver. With a fantastic commentary on the whole trip. With some awesome stories. A credit to the business. Jake was also excellent on the croc boat. Very informative and safety is an absolute priority. Small group of 24 was great also. With pickup and dropoff from where you're staying in Darwin.
author: Wayne Roylance

text: I’ve done this tour before, but this time around was so much better. Our main tour guide, Lloyd, was an absolute legend — super informative, knowledgeable, and just a great bloke all around. For the croc tour, we had Dylan, who brought the energy! He was fun, enthusiastic, and really made the whole experience even more memorable. Flew into Darwin from Melbourne and landed at 2am — and honestly, it was so worth only the 4hour sleep/early wake-up. Highly recommend!
author: teneal wakker

text: A seriously pleasant surprise of how beautiful this area is! It's a pity swimming isn't possible..
author: Sarah Harvey

text: Beautiful look out point with picnic tables.
author: Nicholas Woo

text: Good view heaps of shade
author: David Lynas

text: Great place to see magnificent Darwin sunset with the cliffs and beach as foreground. It wasn't crowded even on a Saturday evening with great weather. Good to bring bug spray though. There were quite a few mosquitoes.
author: KC Lee

text: Beautiful little spot, popular with walkers, joggers,cyclists and people with cameras looking for a nice sunset shot. Interesting to see how much coastal erosion has happened over the past 10 years since I was here last, doesnt look like any efforts have been spent to keep the shore line from falling into the ocean.
author: gasgasLex

text: Thanks Captain Gav for an amazing half day fishing. We had a fantastic time. Gav is both professional and entertaining, ensuring we all had a wonderful time. He took time to assist us all individually when needed, bait cut & ready and rods all rigged up. Highly recommend this trip - the whole package ⭐️
author: anne tr

text: Had a wonderful half day reef experience with Dan. Everyone on the boat caught multiple fish, weather perfect and children had a great time too. Good value, recommended for both new and experienced fishers. Thanks for the experience!
author: David Brown

text: We booked a half day charter and had a awesome time Gav the captain was great put us on the spots time and time again had a great laugh and caught a heap of fish Also learnt about the area as Gav was a wealth of knowledge Definitely recommend
author: Gary Nehls

text: I got my Dad two half-day fishing charter gift certificates for his birthday. We had a terrific day with Paul; he was so professional and friendly. Lots of fish were caught and Paul couldn't have been more helpful or safety conscious. My only regret is that we weren't able to stay for what was sure to be a delicious lunch. Highly recommend.
author: Sarah Fischer

text: Went out twice with Captain Dan. We had plenty of kids on the boat, Dan got them all onto great fish. Dan showed great patience with the younger ones which made the trip enjoyable for all. We caught 100 plus fish in 4 hours with a few great sized Goldies. Dan prepared some that were cooked at a restaurant near the drop off point. I would definitely use this charter again and absolutely recommend it if you are taking kids. On my next trip to Darwin I will definitely try this company again.
author: Chris Kirke

text: Worst shopping experience in woollies after being a regular shoppers for 8 years and a everyday rewards member.. was charged over 200 dollars extra for my grocery bill which I had to point out myself as the checkout person was not happy to be at work or any help
author: ujowal bhattarai

text: For many years i have chosen to go across town especially to shop at Karama Woolies because of the customer service, from the staff stocking the shelves to the staff at the checkouts im always greeted with a smile and treated with respect !
author: Chrissy L

text: Very poor selection of deli products. 1/3 of the display windows are blocked out with black plastic. The range is shrinking every week. Will be moving our business to Coles at Marrara!!!!
author: Rob Montague

text: No competition, service or safety. Or fresh vegetables that I could find. It appears most bakery items have been frozen then thought for your convenience. This area is also often unsafe. Definitely don't go near here if it's getting dark or at night.
author: BRAD

text: I went to Woolworths Karama on Wednesday, November 13th, 2024, around 1:10 pm. A lady near by the reception wearing a vest with ‘I’m here to help’ was very rude and had a bad attitude. If she isn’t happy with her job, she should be wearing a vest that says ‘I’m here to fight.’ Very disappointing shopping experience at Woolworth Karama.
author: James CC

text: Went on the 9am NitNit Dreaming 2 Gorge Tour which was the perfect time of day to miss the heat. Incredible scenery and Tori our tour guide was great. Beautiful part of Australia.
author: Jo Elle

text: Easy to book tours online, confirmation emails are sent with clear directions and instructions on what to bring. This operation runs like clockwork, on time. We did two tours with comments down below for each: Half day Canoe Ferry ride down Gorge to disembark and walk a short way over rocks and steps/metal bridge to the canoes that were lined up ready to go from Gorge . Life jackets issued and instructions… then you are free to make your way up Gorge at your leisure. To enter Gorge , you have to drag the canoe over a few metres of rocks. This is quite difficult as the canoe is quite heavy and the rocks are very slippery and uneven. Gorge - there are a few places to pull up and chill -just avoid the signed crocodile nesting areas. There is plenty of time to do both gorges so take the time to swim and relax as we found we had to kill time - we didn’t need the amount of time allowed. There is cold drinking water back at base and squinchers (iykyk) before you head back on the ferry. Sunset Cruise We assumed we would be in the dinner boat the entire time for some reason, coasting up and down while we sipped our one included bubbly beverage. You depart on a ferry just like the canoe tour on gorge , (rows of seats) then at the beginning of gorge , you disembark on the opposite side to canoe and go on a short walk along which is a very smooth path with only a few steps (400m) to the next ferry that takes you along gorge . After viewing Gorge , you return and walk the return 400m to the dinner boat which has the tables set for dinner. The dinner seats are allocated so you will sit with whoever fits on your table of 4. The meal in general was very nice, we chose the steak for main and it was cooked to perfection - medium rare. The potato was undercooked and tasteless. You have to purchase any other alcoholic beverages. The only disappointment was that we didn’t cruise up and down but stayed in one spot and just went around in a circle and I think this was to create a breeze as it was very very hot and sweaty. Overall, we really enjoyed both our tours and would recommend them. Just be aware that the dinner cruise is pretty much the same tour as the day cruises and you only sit at the table on the way back. The sunset was underwhelming due to the clouds but that’s out of their control haha. The staff were friendly and our tour guide was a comedy show with dad jokes haha
author: Audrey

text: Nitmiluk gorge was spectacular! An absolutely beautiful place to visit. We did a self guided overnight canoe trip. A very disappointing aspect was that we weren't aware of the need to drag our canoe over the rocks to access the separate "gorges" when the water is low. This is horrendous for the environment given the amount of microplastics being left over the rocks!
author: Sarah Harvey

text: Amazing 7 am cruise. Tour guide excellent. Photographic opportunities incredible not only with the rock formations but with the intensely coloured patterns on the surface of the water created by the gentle movement of the boat. I highly recommend this cruise.
author: Ann Stafford

text: Very nice boat tour of Katherine Gorge. Plenty of room on the boat with equal viewing both sides. There is a short walk from one boat to the next for the second gorge. It is an easy walk but I would not recommend for people with mobility issues. Well organised with a knowledgeable guide. Really enjoyed this cruise. Good value for money.
author: Carol Swanwick

text: Very natural springs, not too hot, just warm. Very clear water, with some submerged logs but not a problem. Quite long so lots of people can fit, a bit of current can take you to an end where there are stairs to get out and a path to walk back and do it all again if you don’t want to swim back. About 2 meters deep in middle, most visitors bring noodles especially if not a good swimmer.
author: Chris Reeves

text: Loved the bitter springs or mataranka springs same same, more of a natural setting than the thermal pool. The water is so clear and looks iridescent. It's warm and inviting an easy float down stream with a pool noodle. The car park is a lot smaller than the thermal pool car park difficult for caravans and trailers to park. Only a toilet there with no other amenities. We did see some crocodile traps there Negative was that it was so crowded.
author: Pamela Rivers

text: We loved this place. Stayed at Mataranka homestead camp sites. Toilets and showers are older but clean. There are water stains due to the water. Short walk down to the thermal pools.
author: nicole mathers

text: Water was hot and crystal clear! Great bathing experience, a bit of walk to the waters from the car park. Really well maintained.
author: Maricar Peralta

text: Make sure you go to Bitter springs, which is the nicer version or Mataranka springs. What a beautiful spot, take some snorkels and dive with the fresh water turtles, enjoy this little oasis, please respect this space and take your rubbish with you and enjoy the area in peace and quiet so everyone can enjoy it. Best to visit early in the morning so you can get it to yourselves.
author: Jordy “Outdoorkindaguy”

text: Gorgious spot for sunset, good truck near by and playground for the kids. The atmosphere is pretty calm as well as having community vibes as everyone is out and about. Dog friendly also
author: A Jafa

text: Great for walking the dogs, picnics, cracker night and food trucks. Kids can run around and sunrises and sunsets are spectacular
author: Karina Bourne

text: Sea breezes, high tides and popular food vans. Great place to view the beautiful Darwin sunsets
author: Bernd ruta

text: Absolutely beautiful walk, so relaxing with top views.
author: Flo Morcom

text: Marlow lagoon has a fantastic gated pet park. Quiet when i was there in the early afternoon but have been told later in the afternoon ppl gather, chat and the dogs play and swim...at own risk of course. Terrific kids play areas, cool xylophone & bell donger to keep them amused. Rotundas, bbq's &plenty of places to sit. Even a drinking fountain. Go. Its good
author: Paula Huskisson

text: Hi, here we are Lilly and Skye. Been to Marlow Lagoon Park today. Dad watched out for those crocodiles while we went swimming in the lagoon. Great big park alot of zoomies were had.
author: Tina Hart

text: We are from SA visiting friends. We were blown away with the size and structure of this park. Amazing for dogs and people alike. I think there are 5 different types of areas to suit dogs quiet, small dog etc. there is a playground, toilets, bbq. Well done council.
author: Colleen King

text: Great facility giving owners and dogs exercise. Not sure about the pond water?
author: Karen Gerrard

text: Probably one of the best dog parks in Australia. Pond for swimming, 3 different agility courses for different size dogs, plenty of shade all in a very large fully fenced enclosure. Our doggo loved it
author: Nicholas Mills

text: I stayed for 5 nights in a van and enjoyed a great visit. The park is well run, clean and tidy. It also never felt crowded as it’s quite large. Plenty of toilets and showers which are also clean. Plenty of water pressure and great hot water. I loved the pool especially of an evening as the temperature built up, nice and cooling! It’s easy to get to all the features of the park from here. Highly recommended!
author: Paul Tooze (No Journey Too Small)

text: Based ourselves here while exploring Litchfield N.P. We had a good site with all the amenities you could want. 3 shower amenities clean hot and good pressure. The pool was a very cool (bordering bloody cold) meeting place where a lot of people gathered for a chat and cool down. Fairly easy to get to all the attractions on that side of the park. A great park with reasonable prices.
author: dave Rech

text: We stayed in the powered site. very roomy and grassy. Pleasant staff. And checked on our pooch during the day while we went off exploring. Lovely clean facilities. We enjoyed our stay.
author: Odette Applebee

text: Wonderful place and great places to eat nearby. We had a lovely cabin tucked away under some trees. It was very quiet and peaceful (April). The cabin was clean with everything we needed and nice outside sitting areas. The staff were extremely helpful and cheerful and went out of their way to help us with a problem. They couldn't have been better. I would highly recommend this place to anyone wanting to stay in this area.
author: Deborah Blackie

text: Had 6 nights here and check out tomorrow! Love love loved the van park. Their facilities of having the cafe there for breaky lunch is fab even though we only grabbed ice cream n milk n bread. We were in a gorg grassy site on the corner of the block with the paddock in front of us and big expanse between our site and fence to paddock with cows & the odd pigs which we saw only tonight in there. Wallabies come out morn and evening and can have a heap of eyes looking at you from the park lawns as they come around the park, round the van sites its fabulous. So very peaceful. Pool is a great addition and lovely and refreshing. Other facilities around about the van park are in great working order, the grounds are kept lovely. Friendly and helpful staff. 2 huge days in Litchfield N.P were amazing. Loved it all esp the 4wd track to Surprise falls. Thanks all
author: Sandy Boyd

text: What an amazing experience. I highly recommend visiting while in the area. Rock paintings are estimated to be over 5000 years old. Stories are shown alongside. You can just go to the "gallery" area or the whole way up to the lookout over Arnhem Land which I recommend. Visually stunning and moving. Climbing over uneven rocks is necessary but there are some bannisters installed. Limited mobility may not make it to the very top as there is free climbing involved. Car park and toilets available.
author: Kim S

text: A trip to Kakadu wouldn’t be complete without visiting the incredible art at Ubirr. The detail, the complexity and the range of styles was mind blowing. Keep your voices low and you’ll hear and see a great deal of wildlife too.
author: Lizzie Smith

text: This place is full of history amazing views and art. We loved the walk through was very exciting to see the views and the awesome art there. Definitely worth the walk for sure.
author: Daniel Torrance

text: The walking trail from the carpark is a flat easy walk. Getting up close to see the rock art involves some rough steps to access them. Amazing detail can be seen on some areas but the weather and time has faded others. Some drawings of the images are shown on signs which helps to see the shapes and locate the images. Toilets in the carpark were clean.
author: Louise Tome

text: Amazing short walk through some rock art. Not far from the carpark. The option to walk a little further to the lookout which overlooks the flood Plains.
author: jodie huitema

text: My wife and I visited the Cutta Cutta Caves today and had a fantastic experience. The caves themselves are beautiful and fascinating, but what really made the tour special was our guide. They were incredibly knowledgeable, personable, and explained not only the geological features of the caves but also the mythology and local history behind them.
